@CtmGamer, the other things aren't affected by the filter because the thing that is being affected by the filter is captured as an image, using `get()`, then it's drawn using `image()`, instead of calling the function again.  So, it will get the colour data for each of the pixels, then redraw those pixels, instead of running the drawing code again.  Think of it as drawing something on a piece of paper, and smudging that drawing up, so that it's blurred.  Then, you get a camera, take a picture of that drawing, then print it out, and slap it onto another drawing.    So, the blurred drawing doesn't affect the other drawing. That's basically what happens.  If you don't use `get()` and `image()`, but instead use a function and call it, it would be the same as drawing something onto a previous drawing, then smudging the whole thing up, so the whole thing is blurred.
